## Step 2 — Explain: Complete Implementation Plan

---

### 2.1 Architecture Decision

**Single-page wizard, local form state, sequential API submission on final step.**

**Why this architecture:**

- The TRD (Section 11) confirms: "No global state library (Redux/Zustand) is needed at MVP scale." Local React state per step is sufficient.
- Data is committed to the API only on final "Finish" — not step-by-step. This avoids creating a half-configured semester in the database if the user abandons setup halfway.
- This is the simplest implementation that satisfies the documentation and is appropriate for a solo developer.

**Why NOT step-by-step API commits:**

- Step-by-step commits would require cleanup logic if the user exits mid-wizard, adding complexity with no SRD-documented benefit.

---

### 2.2 Wizard Steps (Exactly 5, Per SRD Section 20)

| Step # | Name | SRD Source |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | Semester Details | SRD Section 10.1.a — Semester start/end date |
| 2 | Attendance Policy | SRD Section 10.1.b — Min overall %, min subject % |
| 3 | Subjects & Attendance | SRD Section 10.1.d — Subject name, code, held/present |
| 4 | Weekly Timetable | SRD Section 10.1.c — Per weekday, slots with subject/time |
| 5 | Semester Events | SRD Section 10.1.e — Event type, dates, flag overrides (optional/skippable) |

A final **Review & Submit** screen summarizes all entered data before the API calls are made.

**Why this specific step order?**

The SRD defines it explicitly. Timetable is Step 4 (not Step 3) because you need Subjects defined first — each timetable slot references a `subject_id`, and users will select subjects from a dropdown in the timetable builder. Subjects must exist in local state before the timetable step renders.

